    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. It sounds pretty intense. One part of the clause mentions \"unforeseen liabilities and indirect damages.\" It feels a bit like they're trying to catch me on things I can't even see coming. Are there specific types of \"sneaky\" or unexpected traps in these kinds of clauses that I should be specifically scanning for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Unforeseen liabilities and indirect damages\"—that phrasing is definitely the kind of language that makes a contract feel as murky as a swamp, and you're right to be wary. These phrases are often used by the stronger party to cast a very wide net, hoping to catch you when you least expect it.\n\nThe \"sneaky\" traps here usually revolve around the *scope* of what they consider \"indirect.\" While direct damages are usually the immediate, obvious cost (like the cost to fix a broken server), indirect damages cover consequential losses—the ripple effects. For example, if your breach causes their system to go down, the direct damage is the cost of the downtime; the *indirect* damage might be the lost profits they suffered because their customers couldn't buy anything while the system was down. If you haven't specifically carved out or limited these, you could be liable for their entire business's lost revenue, which is a massive, unpredictable financial burden.\n\nIt's almost always a negotiation point. You want to limit liability to direct, foreseeable damages only. If they insist on keeping \"unforeseen liabilities,\" you need to ask *how* they define \"unforeseen.\"",
      "source": "target",
